import cv2
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
In [2]:
def plot_side_by_side(image1, title1, image2, title2,x,y):
    fig, (img1, img2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(x, y))
    img1.imshow(image1)
    img2.imshow(image2) 
    img1.set_title(title1)
    img2.set_title(title2)
    #img1.axis("off")
    #img2.axis("off")
    plt.show()

Note: "SE" represents -> Structuring Element

Question 1¶

In [3]:
image1 = cv2.imread('Square-circle.png',1)
In [4]:
image_dilated_sq = cv2.dilate(image1,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_RECT,(25,25)),iterations = 1)
image_dilated_cir = cv2.dilate(image1,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE,(25,25)),iterations = 1)

plot_side_by_side(image1,"Original Image",image_dilated_sq,"After dilation using square SE",10,10 )
plot_side_by_side(image1,"Original Image",image_dilated_cir,"After dilation using circle SE",10,10 )

Observations: When using square and circle kernels with same size, the black hole has totally disappeared in case square but in case circle it has not disappeared.

Question 3¶

In [7]:
image3 = cv2.imread('lady.png',1)
In [8]:
dilated = cv2.dilate(image3,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_RECT,(3,3)),iterations = 1)

edges = cv2.Canny(image3,100,200)
fig, (img1, img2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 10))
img1.imshow(image3)
plt.imshow(edges,"gray")
img1.set_title("Original Image")
img2.set_title("Edge Detection using Canny before dilation")
plt.show()

edges = cv2.Canny(dilated,100,200)
fig, (img1, img2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 10))
img1.imshow(dilated)
plt.imshow(edges,"gray")
img1.set_title("Dilated Image")
img2.set_title("Edge Detection using Canny after dilation")
plt.show()

Note: When we used canny for original image and made edge detection ,the edges were not clear enough, but after dilation, the edges became more clear and presice.

Question 4¶

In [9]:
image4 = cv2.imread('Circle.png',1)
In [10]:
erosion_sq = cv2.erode(image4,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_RECT,(17,17)),iterations = 1)
plot_side_by_side(image4,"Original Image",erosion_sq,"After Erosion using square SE" ,10,10)

erosion_cir = cv2.erode(image4,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE,(17,17)),iterations = 1)
plot_side_by_side(image4,"Original Image",erosion_cir,"After Erosion using circle SE",10,10 )

Note: when we used circle kernel the black balls kept their shape as circles, but when we used square kernel the black balls changed their shape to be closer to squares not circles.

Question 5¶

In [11]:
image5 = cv2.imread('Circle.png',1)
#image5 = cv2.cvtColor(image5, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
In [12]:
inverted1 = 255 - image5
plot_side_by_side(image5,"Original Image",inverted1,"Inverted Image",10,10 )

retval,thresholded = cv2.threshold(inverted1,175,255,cv2.THRESH_BINARY)
erosion_ = cv2.erode(thresholded,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE,(9,9)),iterations = 2)
plot_side_by_side(thresholded,"Thresholded 'Inverted' Image",erosion_,"After Erosion Twice",10,10 )

inverted_back = 255 - erosion_ 
plt.imshow(inverted_back)
plt.title("Final Image")
plt.show()

Here we could to separate the balls from each other using thresholding and erosion.

Question 7¶

In [15]:
image7 = cv2.imread('Circle_and_Lines.png',1)
In [16]:
opened = cv2.morphologyEx(image7, cv2.MORPH_OPEN, cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE,(11,11)))
plot_side_by_side(image7,"Original Image",opened,"After opening 'Circles'",10,10 )

dilation_cir = cv2.dilate(opened,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE,(3,3)))

subtract = image7-dilation_cir
dilation_lin = cv2.dilate(subtract,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE,(15,15)))
plot_side_by_side(subtract,"After subtraction to get lines",dilation_lin,"dilation lines",10,10 )
erosion_lin = cv2.erode(dilation_lin,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_RECT,(3,3)),iterations = 3)
plt.imshow(erosion_lin)
plt.title("erosin lines again")
plt.show()
In [17]:
#algorithm to count circles
can = cv2.Canny(opened,100,200)
im2, circle_contours, hierarchy  = cv2.findContours(can.copy(),cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL, cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)
print ("Circles Count: " ,len(circle_contours))

closed = cv2.erode(thresholded,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_CROSS,(3,3)),iterations = 1)
skeleton = thresholded - closed
dilated_dog= cv2.dilate(skeleton,cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_CROSS,(3,3)),iterations = 1)

plt.title("Dog Skeleton")
plt.show()
